You must be able to explain some specifics about this infrastructure:

For every additional element, why you are adding it
 - Two new servers to remove a SPOF, make maintenance easier and increase availability
 - HA Proxy to enable Round Robin Balancing between all servers

What distribution algorithm your load balancer is configured with and how it works
 - For the sake of the task we will use Round Robin balancing. 
 - This means requests will be assigned one to each server in order, first to last and then first again.
 - With this distribution all servers have an equal amount of requests. 
 - However, this does not balance around the weight of the requests but rather to the number of them.

Is your load-balancer enabling an Active-Active or Active-Passive setup, explain the difference between both.
 - The load-balancer uses an active-active setup to ensure we can benefit from performance of multiple servers.
 - This means we have all servers active at all times and we just distribute workload between them.
 - In a active-pasive setup we would have only one active server and use the remaining in case the main one goes down.

How a database Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) cluster works
 - This schema works by having a primary database to write into and work as "main branch".
 - Secundary(slave) nodes will just copy from the main node and only allow reads.

What is the difference between the Primary node and the Replica node in regard to the application
 - Replica nodes are only for backup or database reads.
 - New entries can only be inserted into the main node(s).


You must be able to explain what the issues are with this infrastructure:

Where are SPOF
 - We no longer have a single main server as a SPOF and with two more servers we can have redundancy.
 - However, now our infrastructure depends on a singular(1) load-balancer, so our application will fail if it goes down.

Security issues (no firewall, no HTTPS)
 - We have no HTTPS meaning no encryption to our request so we are vulnerable to man in the middle attacks.
 - We cannot block certain requests or IPs since we have no firewall.

No monitoring
 - We have no insight of how our server is doing internally.
 - We don't know hardware usage or any internal configuration errors.
 - We have to manually check if our application is running or if any erros occurred.
